Package org.e2immu.annotation

package org.e2immu.annotation
  • Enum Class Summary
    Enum Class
    Description
    AnnotationMode
    The names of two annotation modes.
  • Annotation Interfaces Summary
    Annotation Interface
    Description
    AllowsInterrupt
    Annotation indicating that this method or constructor increases the statement time, in other words, allows the execution to be interrupted.
    BeforeMark
    Annotation computed when an eventually immutable type is guaranteed to be in its _before_ state, i.e., none of the marked methods have been called yet.
    Constant
    Annotation to indicate that field has been assigned, or a method returns, a constant value.
    Container
    An annotation on a type (computed on a class, contracted on an interface) that indicates that no method of the type modifies its parameters.
    Dependent
    Opposite of @Independent.
    Dependent1
    Annotation to indicate content linking: a parameter of implicitly immutable type is assigned to a field; or an implicitly immutable part of the object graph of a field is returned by a method.
    Dependent2
    The annotation indicates that part of the implicitly immutable content of this parameter (or method result) content links to the implicitly immutable content of the fields.
    E1Container
    Short-hand for the combination of E1Immutable and Container.
    E1Immutable
    Annotation marking that the type is effectively or eventually level 1 immutable: all fields are (eventually) Final.
    E2Container
    Short-hand for the combination of E2Immutable and Container.
    E2Immutable
    Annotation indicating that the type is effectively or eventually level 2 immutable: it is E1Immutable, all its fields are NotModified, fields of non-implicitly immutable type are either private or level 2 immutable themselves, and non-private methods and constructors are Independent.
    ExtensionClass
    Annotation indicating that a type is an extension class of another type E.
    Final
    Annotation indicating that a field is effectively or eventually final: it is never assigned to outside constructors or methods only reachable from constructors.
    Finalizer
    Annotation on a method, always contracted, indicating that after calling this method, no other methods may be called anymore on the object.
    Fluent
    Annotation indicating that the method returns 'this', and allows for chaining.
    Identity
    Annotation indicating that the method returns its first parameter.
    IgnoreModifications
    Annotation used to indicate that modifications on a field can be ignored.
    Independent
    Annotation indicating that On a non-modifying method, the return value does not link to the fields; on a constructor, none of the parameters link to any of the fields.
    Linked
    Annotation used for debugging purposes only: it explains, or verifies, if and where a field links to.
    Linked1
    Annotation used for debugging purposes only: it explains, or verifies, if and where a field content links to.
    Mark
    Annotation indicating that this modifying method transitions an eventually immutable object from the before state to the after state.
    Modified
    Opposite of NotModified.
    Modified1
    Annotation used to indicate that the subject of the annotation (a parameter, the method result, a field) has been the object of an abstract method which potentially modifies the implicitly immutable content of the object passed to the abstract method.
    MutableModifiesArguments
    Present when a type is neither Container nor E1Immutable.
    NotModified
    Indicates that no modifications took place in the method; that the parameter's content was not modified, that no method modifies the content of the field.
    NotModified1
    Annotation used to indicate that the subject of the annotation (a parameter, the method result, a field) has been the object of an abstract method which is guaranteed not to modify the implicitly immutable content of the object passed to the abstract method.
    NotNull
    On a method, this annotation indicates that the return value is never null.
    NotNull1
    Content not null, one level up from not null.
    NotNull2
    This annotation indicates that the object is NotNull, its content is NotNull, and the content of its content is NotNull.
    Nullable
    Opposite of NotNull: indicates that the method, field or parameter potentially (but not necessarily) holds the null value.
    Only
    This annotation is part of the eventual immutability computations.
    PropagateModification
    Indicates that an abstract method has been called on this parameter, and modification needs propagating to the place of calling.
    Singleton
    Annotation used to indicate that a class is a singleton: only one instance can be created.
    TestMark
    Annotation to mark a non-modifying method, returning a boolean indicating whether the object is in the after state (true, marked) or in the before state (false, not yet marked).
    UtilityClass
    Annotation on a type to indicate that the type is a well-formed utility class: The class is level 2 immutable, all its methods are static, and the class cannot be instantiated: all its constructors are private, and there is at least one; none of these methods call the constructors.
    Variable
    Opposite of Final: this annotation indicates that a field is not effectively or eventually final.
